e trace through the actual example to clarify what's really happening here. I'm re-reading the source more carefully now. The statement about User class's setName method having @Required and @Length annotations seems inconsistent with the actual code shown, where User's setName only has @PropertyName. This looks like it might be an error in the source material—it should probably reference UserBase's setName instead. The knowledge file doesn't quote this specific passage directly, but it does correctly capture the core point that parent class annotations are used for validation. Moving forward with section 2 on internationalization.\n\nFor internationalized applications, display names need to be registered in the message management system for each language rather than hardcoding them in @PropertyName's value attribute. There are two ways to link property names to their display names: using the messageId attribute in @PropertyName, or following the convention of using \"<ClassName>.<propertyName>\" as the message ID. The knowledge file handles this section accurately.\n\nWhen using the messageId attribute approach, I specify a message ID that gets resolved from the message resource file instead of using the value attribute directly. The code examples show this with IDs like PROP0001 and PROP0002, along with their corresponding message table entries.\n\nAlternatively, I can use the \"<Form class name>.<property name>\" pattern as the message ID without needing @PropertyName at all, as long as ValidationManager is configured with useFormPropertyNameAsMessageId=true. The key insight here is that @PropertyName becomes optional when using this convention-based approach.\n\nNow I'm weighing the two methods. Method 1 with explicit messageId attributes gives me precise control over message ID management, but it requires careful coordination and makes auto-generating entities difficult. Method 2 with the class.property naming convention eliminates the need for annotations and 